'''Isaac Saba Raffoul''' (October 17, 1923 – July 27, 2008) was a [[Mexico|Mexican]] businessman of [[Syrian Jewish]] origin; his father emigrated from [[Aleppo]], [[Syria]] to [[Veracruz, Veracruz|Veracruz]], [[Mexico]] where he started a rag business<ref>[http://data2.efinf.com/reader/display?c=lores&id=29b0df3f2d73af4143c3e1a510e74e05&d=2006-12-10 El delito fiscal de Isaac Saba] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090906171526/http://data2.efinf.com/reader/display?c=lores&id=29b0df3f2d73af4143c3e1a510e74e05&d=2006-12-10 |date=2009-09-06 }}</ref> which the family built on. Isaac Saba Raffoul was one of the [[wealthiest persons in the world]] according to ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/billions/2010/01/11/another-billionaire-family-tragedy/#1ae5f9225da9|title=Another Billionaire Family Tragedy|last=Thibault|first=Marie|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-07-23|language=en}}</ref> He had been married with wife Rebecca for over 40 years and had three sons: Moises, Manuel and Alberto.
He was the president of [[Grupo Xtra]] and chairman of [[Casa Saba]]. There has been a controversy surrounding him since he teamed up with [[General Electric]] Mexico to open up a new nationwide television channel. [[TV Azteca]] and [[Televisa]], upon hearing this, accused him of monopolizing medicine prices in an attempt to discredit him. According to El Financiero, there is no such monopoly.<ref>[http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/ElFinanciero/Portal/cfpages/contentmgr.cfm?docId=34429&docTipo=1&orderby=docid&sortby=ASC El Financiero en línea<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> After his death in 2008, his two youngest sons Alberto and Manuel inherited the ownership of the company.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.americaeconomia.com/negocios-industrias/cuando-la-sucesion-generacional-no-funciona-en-las-empresas|title=Cuando la sucesión generacional no funciona en las empresas|access-date=2018-07-23|language=es}}</ref>
